<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1312,2034]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">
Valves linear with parallel or, in larger specimens, weakly undulated margins, and non-protracted, broadly rounded apices. Valve dimensions (n=11): length 
<quantity box="[754,880,1350,1376]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="30.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="25.0">25–35 µm</quantity>
, width 5.0– 
<quantity box="[1025,1114,1350,1376]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 µm</quantity>
. Axial area narrow, linear, clearly widening towards the central area. Central area forming a large rhombic fascia, about 1/3 to 1/4 of valve length, expanded to the margins. Raphe slightly curved. Central raphe endings extending into the central area well beyond the last central striae, unilaterally deflected and finishing in relatively distant drop-like pores. Terminal fissures almost indistinct,?-shaped. Striae strongly radiate in the middle, abruptly changing their direction to convergent toward the valve ends, 
<quantity box="[761,864,1544,1570]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" metricValueMax="3.302" metricValueMin="2.794" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="in" value="12.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="11.0">11–13 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[871,950,1544,1570]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. Longitudinal lines absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1312,2034]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,509,1582,1608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Habitat and distribution</emphasis>
:—This is an extremely rare species on Livingston Island. Only a few valves were found on Hurd Peninsula, in streams, in a vegetation of wet mosses close to streams, brooks or puddles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1312,2034]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,403,1659,1685]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Observations:—</emphasis>
These Antarctic specimens belong to the complex of species around 
<taxonomicName box="[1221,1436,1660,1685]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="divergentissima">
<emphasis box="[1221,1436,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">P. divergentissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Grunow in 
<bibRefCitation author="Cleve, P. T. &amp; Moller, J. D." box="[295,608,1699,1725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" refId="ref14879" refString="Cleve, P. T. &amp; Moller, J. D. (1879) Collection of 324 diatom slides with accompanying analices of A. Grunow. Part 3, 38 pp. Uppsala." type="book" year="1879">Cleve &amp; Möller 1879: 186</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Cleve, P. T." box="[624,823,1699,1725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 220" refId="ref14851" refString="Cleve, P. T. (1895) Synopsis of the Naviculoid diatoms. Kongliga Svenska Vetenskaps-Akademiens Handlingar 27 (3): 1 - 220." type="journal article" year="1895">Cleve (1895: 77)</bibRefCitation>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K." box="[904,1105,1699,1725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" refId="ref15524" refString="Krammer, K. (2000) The genus Pinnularia. In: H. Lange-Bertalot (ed.), Diatoms of Europe, Diatoms of the European Inland waters and comparable habitats. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag K. G., 1: 703 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krammer (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[1117,1436,1699,1724]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="divergentissima">
<emphasis box="[1117,1436,1699,1724]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Pinnularia divergentissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its varieties can be separated based on a different valve outline, having mostly convex margins and smaller subrostrate to capitate valve ends, as well as by a slightly higher number of striae (according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K." box="[151,417,1814,1840]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" refId="ref15524" refString="Krammer, K. (2000) The genus Pinnularia. In: H. Lange-Bertalot (ed.), Diatoms of Europe, Diatoms of the European Inland waters and comparable habitats. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag K. G., 1: 703 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krammer 2000: 12–14</bibRefCitation>
vs 
<quantity box="[457,558,1814,1840]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" metricValueMax="3.302" metricValueMin="2.794" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="in" value="12.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="11.0">11–13 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[566,643,1814,1840]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
) and a smaller central area. The most similar species is 
<taxonomicName authority="Metzeltin" authorityName="Metzeltin" authorityYear="1996" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[1293,1436,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">P. krammeri</emphasis>
Metzeltin
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H. &amp; Metzeltin, D." box="[313,762,1853,1879]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 390" refId="ref15707" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H. &amp; Metzeltin, D. (1996) Oligotrophie-Indikatoren. 800 Taxa reprasentativ fur drei diverse Seen- Typen. Iconographia Diatomologica 2: 1 - 390." type="journal article" year="1996">Lange-Bertalot &amp; Metzeltin 1996: 98</bibRefCitation>
), described from 
<collectingCountry box="[971,1065,1853,1879]" name="Finland" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Finland</collectingCountry>
. The main differences between the Antarctic population and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Metzeltin" authorityYear="1996" box="[490,632,1892,1917]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[490,632,1892,1917]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">P.krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include a larger valve width of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Metzeltin" authorityYear="1996" box="[1001,1143,1892,1917]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[1001,1143,1892,1917]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">P. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[1165,1301,1892,1918]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" metricValueMax="7.8" metricValueMin="6.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="7.25" valueMax="7.8" valueMin="6.7">6.7–7.8 µm</quantity>
vs. 5.0– 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 µm</quantity>
), a comparably smaller central area and more closely spaced proximal raphe endings. Since only a few valves have been observed, it is too early to conclude whether they should be described as an independent species or belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Metzeltin" authorityYear="1996" box="[392,534,2008,2033]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[392,534,2008,2033]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">P. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
